Terrain Types and Features
**************************

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{i}Plain: @{ui} This is basic ground level, open plain, and is what all
     movement times are based on. The base movement time for a Plain
     hex is given in the status display.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{i}Sand: @{ui} It takes three times as long to move thru sand and it
     adds 2 pts of heat per second.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{i}Snow: @{ui} It takes twice as long to move thru snow, and there is a
     chance that you will slip on the ice. Snow will remove 2 pts of
     heat per second.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{i}Light Forest: @{ui} It takes twice as long to move through light
     forest as across plains, and makes you one point harder to hit.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{i}Heavy Forest: @{ui} It takes three times as long to move through
     heavy forest and you are two points harder to hit.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{i}Jungle: @{ui} You can not move thru this hex. It is possible to jump
     over it, but if you land in a Jungle hex the only way out is to
     jump. Jungle hexes can be burned.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{i}Swamp: @{ui} It takes twice as long to move, you are one point
     easier to hit, and there is a good chance of slipping and falling.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{i}Shallow Water: @{ui} This type hex takes twice as long to move
     through and makes it easier for you to be hit and harder for you
     to hit others, but helps you to cool down. The water will remove 3
     points of heat per second in addition to your heat sinks. There is
     a chance you will slip and fall.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{i}Medium Water: @{ui} This type water is up to the mechs waist.
     Weapons below the waist can not be fired. You get 6 points of
     cooling per second, but you are easier to hit and it is harder for
     you to aim. You can't kick in medium water. Move at 1/3 normal
     rate.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{i}Deep Water: @{ui} This type water provides 9 points of
     cooling/second.  Weapons below the neck can not be fired and you
     are very hard to hit. You can't kick or punch in deep water. Move
     at 1/4 normal rate.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{i}Bottomless Water: @{ui} This type water is beyond your mechs
     capability.  It will crush your mech, destroying it and killing
     you. The only way past this type of hex is to jump over.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{i}Low Hills: @{ui} Hills provide cover. You can't shoot over them.
     Low hills make it one point easier to hit mechs below you. Move at
     1/3 normal rate uphill or half normal rate on the same level.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{i}Medium Hills: @{ui} You get two extra points to hit mechs below you
     due to height. Move at 2 + 1/level going uphill.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{i}High Hills: @{ui} You get three extra points to hit mechs below you
     due to height. Hills have a tactical advantage, but beware of
     skill rolls.  If you fall you can roll all the down, doing
     multiple damage.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{i}Barrier Peak: @{ui} This hex type is impassible. You can not jump
     over it. It is used for obstacles. All Arena maps have a border of
     Barrier Peaks.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{i}Fire: @{ui} Energy and Missile weapons can start forest fires.
     Moving or stopping in a forest fire adds a 6 points of heat per
     second to your mech, and the smoke adds three points on all hit
     rolls. Move at half normal rate.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{i}Cleared: @{ui} Cannons and Missiles can clear trees from forest
     hexes.  This is rough terrain, move at half normal rate. Cannons
     and Missiles can also be used to 'blow out' forest fires.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{i}Burned: @{ui} Once a forest fire has burned out the hex becomes
     rough terrain. Move at half normal rate.

   Terrain plays an important part in combat strategy. A good position
can mean the difference between winning and loosing. Use the terrain to
your advantage. If you try to leave the map area you will be asked if
your wish to ESCAPE from the combat. If you say Yes, your mech will be
removed at the end of the move and you are out of the game. Forests are
much harder to see through at ground level. If you are at ground level
and the mech you are trying to see is also at ground level you can only
see through three light woods or one light and one heavy woods.


@EndNode

